Pediatric Sleep Apnea

Background - Obstructive sleep apnea is common problem (1-6%) characterized by partial or complete obstruction of the upper airways during sleep - Associated with CNS, CVS morbidity - Diagnosis is dependant on Polysomnography- cumbersome and costly

Project Question- are there noninvasive markers of obstructive sleep apnea?

Pediatric Sleep Apnea METHODS

Methods Childhood Adenotonisllectomy test

  • multi-center, single-blind, randomized, controlled trial ages 5 to 9.9 years with mild to moderate sleep apnea -randomized to watchful waiting or eAT followed over 7-month observation period assesed pre and post neurocognitive functioning, growth parameters, metabolic outcomes and quality of life -1,447 children had screening polysomnographs and 464 were randomized to treatment. -variables of interest: history(allergies, bedwetting, mouth breathing), physical exam factors(obesity, inflammation on blood test, enlarged tonsils), easily measurable metrics(heart rate variability) ## Datasets import

Conclusions

Tonsillar hypertrophy, mouth breathing, Heart Rate Variability may be indicators of OSA in pediatric patients

Limitations- selected population

Future-include children without OSA, further explore mouthbreathing and heartrate variability

PSG still the Gold Standard!
